BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
a.  Proof by contradiction. Start of proof: Assume, for the sake of contradiction, that there are integers [`x`] and [`y`] such that [`x`] is a prime greater than 5 and [`x = 6y + 3\text{.}`] End of proof: ... this is a contradiction, so there are no such integers.

a.  Direct proof. Start of proof: Let [`n`] be an integer. Assume [`n`] is a multiple of 3. End of proof: Therefore [`n`] can be written as the sum of consecutive integers.

a.  Proof by contrapositive. Start of proof: Let [`a`] and [`b`] be integers. Assume that [`a`] and [`b`] are even. End of proof: Therefore [`a^2 + b^2`] is even.

END_PGML_SOLUTION

